# Day 9 - Script Execution Permissions

## Task
Grant read and execute permissions to `/tmp/xfusioncorp.sh` on App Server 1 for all users.

## Objective
Practice modifying Linux file permissions to allow all users to execute a shell script.

## Commands Used
```bash
ssh tony@stapp01

# Check existing permissions
ls -la /tmp/xfusioncorp.sh

# Grant read and execute to all users
sudo chmod a+rx /tmp/xfusioncorp.sh

# Verify
ls -la /tmp/xfusioncorp.sh
```

## What the Commands Do
- `ls -la` shows the file permissions before and after the change.
- `chmod a+rx` grants read and execute permissions to all users (owner, group, others).
- `a` targets all users, `+` adds permissions, `r` is read, `x` is execute.

## Verification
Before: `----------` — no permissions for anyone.  
After: `-r-xr-xr-x` — read and execute for all users confirmed.

## What I Learned
- How Linux file permissions are structured for owner, group, and others.
- How `chmod a+rx` applies permissions to all user categories at once.
- Why write permission is intentionally excluded from executable scripts.

## Personal Notes
This task highlighted that even root-owned files can have no permissions set by default. It also reinforced why scripts should be executable but not writable by all users.
